ce:section.ce:para:
The synthesis route of FG/rCQDs was displayed in Fig. 1
                        a, where the carbon quantum dots (CQDs) with the horizontal size of ∼0.9–1.1 nm was selected as the intercalation species. In a nutshell, CQDs adsorb first on the exfoliated FG surface under the action of electrostatic force, the FG/rCQDs nanosheets were obtained after a reduction process. It can be displayed that all characteristic signals of bulk FGi by X-ray diffraction (XRD) patterns as shown in Fig. 1b [37]. The (002) peak at ∼21.4° has a significant shift to the right, reflecting the increase of interlayer spacing. This demonstrates the successful intercalation of CQDs into FGi gallery and the significant expansion of interlayer spacing from 0.42 to 1.08 nm. It is well documented that the achieved interlayer spacing of 1.08 nm is the largest value among all those previous studies [38]. As shown in Raman spectra and Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy (FTIR) (Fig. 1c and 1d), the relatively increased graphitic carbon vibration (G) in FG/rCQDs compared with the CQDs manifest the reduction from CQDs to rCQDs. Moreover, the increase of ID/IG demonstrated that intercalation of CQDs can introduce more defects into FGi, simultaneously proving the insertion of a large number of CQDs. Compared with the bulk FGi, the obtained FG/rCQDs still remain a lot of fluorine, which demonstrates that intercalation of CQDs will not greatly destroy the components of FGi. Transmission electron microscopy (TEM, Fig. 1e and Fig. 1g-h) images shown that CQDs presents the tiny size in the range of 0.7–1.8 nm. Moreover, after intercalation, the interlayer spacing of FGi increased from 0.42 to 1.08 (Fig. S1-2
                        ), which provide preconditions for the intercalation of CQDs. Increased layer spacing implies weak interlayer interaction, which provides the basis for reducing microscopic friction force.
